5	// ── WHY THIS CLASS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
6	// A real Factory: its whole job is to translate the primitive choice (a
7	// StrategyType enum) plus a policy into the matching strategy OBJECT. The service
8	// never writes `new TokenBucketStrategy(...)` itself — it asks the factory. That
9	// keeps the "which class for which enum" decision in exactly one place, so adding
10	// a third algorithm touches only this switch and the enum.
11	// 🎙️ "The factory's only job is enum-to-object: hand it TOKEN_BUCKET and a
12	//      policy, it builds a token-bucket strategy. The service stays ignorant of
13	//      the concrete classes, so a new algorithm is one new case here."
14	public final class StrategyFactory {
15	
16	    private final StrategyType type;
17	
18	    public StrategyFactory(StrategyType type) {
19	        this.type = type;
20	    }
21	
22	    // WHY: a FRESH strategy per customer. Each customer needs its own running
23	    //      state (token count / timestamp log), so we build a new instance every
24	    //      time a customer is registered — never share one across customers.
25	    // WHY: startNanos is passed so the token bucket knows when its lazy-refill
26	    //      clock started; without it a customer registered later would over-refill.
27	    public RateLimitStrategy create(RateLimitPolicy policy, long startNanos) {
28	        return switch (type) {
29	            case TOKEN_BUCKET -> new TokenBucketStrategy(policy, startNanos);
30	            case SLIDING_WINDOW -> new SlidingWindowLogStrategy(policy);
31	        };
32	    }
33	}
